This course contemplates the history and contemporary practice of human experimentation. In this course, students consider famous and infamous cases of both real and fictional human experimentation as well as less frequently discussed cases of human experimentation that take place everyday in the contemporary world. Real cases draw from medicine, physiology, psychology, and anthropology; fictional cases draw from literature and film. 
&#8232;Students “really enjoyed this class”, and found the course topics to be interesting and topics “very well planned out”. One student advised taking this course “as early in their academic career at Penn as possible,” as the writing skills learned will be beneficial in future classes. &#8232;
&#8232;Professor Johnson was lauded for planning the course out very well, but one student complained of his policies regarding tardiness to class.&#8232;&#8232;
The workload for this course was described as being “a lot”, with an essay due every week, and students felt unsure of where they stood grade-wise but such comments were consistent across many writing courses.

